              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\to  B]]></fr:tex> be a local homomorphism (N.B. all rings are now Noetherian), and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {m}]]></fr:tex> be the maximal ideal of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
    Then the following conditions are equivalent:</fr:p>
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;i. &quot;">
      <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B/\mathfrak {m}B]]></fr:tex> is of finite dimension over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k=A/\mathfrak {m}]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>

    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;ii. &quot;">
      <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {m}B]]></fr:tex> is an ideal of definition, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B/\mathfrak {r}(B)=k(B)]]></fr:tex> is an extension of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k=k(A)]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>

    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;iii. &quot;">
      The completion <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\widehat {B}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is finite over the completion <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\widehat {A}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>

  </html:ol>
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>If the conditions of <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.2.1" href="sga1-i.2.1.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="I.2.1" /> are satisfied, then we say that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>quasi-finite</fr:em> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
  A morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  Y]]></fr:tex> is said to be quasi-finite at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> (or the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>-prescheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is said to be quasi-finite at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>) if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_x]]></fr:tex> is quasi-finite over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{f(x)}]]></fr:tex>.
  This is equivalent to saying that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>isolated in its fibre <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}(x)]]></fr:tex></fr:em>.
  A morphism is said to be quasi-finite if it is quasi-finite at each point.
  (In [EGA II 6.2.3] we further suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is of finite type.)</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
