          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  Y]]></fr:tex> be a morphism of finite type.
    For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> to be an open immersion, it is necessary and sufficient that it be <fr:em>étale</fr:em> and <fr:em>radicial</fr:em>.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>357</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#254</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-254.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>sga1-i.5.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Recall what "radicial" means: injective, with radicial residual extensions (recall also that it means that the morphism remains injective under any base extension).
      The necessity is trivial, and the sufficiency remains to be shown.
      We are going to give two different proofs: the first is shorter, the second is more elementary.</fr:p>

    <fr:ol><fr:li>A flat morphism is open, and so we can suppose (by replacing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(X)]]></fr:tex>) that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is an onto <fr:em>homeomorphism</fr:em>.
        For any base extension, it remains true that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is flat, radicial, and surjective, thus a homeomorphism, and a fortiori closed.
        Thus <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>proper</fr:em>.
        Thus <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>finite</fr:em> (reference: Chevalley's theorem), defined by a coherent sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {B}]]></fr:tex> of algebras.
        Now <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {B}]]></fr:tex> is locally free, and further, by hypothesis, of rank 1 everywhere, and so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X=Y]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>

      <fr:li>We can suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> are <fr:em>affine</fr:em>.
        We can further easily reduce to proving the following:
        if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y=\operatorname {Spec}(A)]]></fr:tex>, with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> local, and if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}(y)]]></fr:tex> is non-empty (where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> is the closed point of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>), then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X=Y]]></fr:tex> (indeed, this would imply that every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\in  f(X)]]></fr:tex> has an open neighbourhood <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X|U=U]]></fr:tex>).
        We will then have that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X=\operatorname {Spec}(B)]]></fr:tex>, and wish to prove that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A=B]]></fr:tex>.
        But for this we can reduce to proving the analogous claim where we replace <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\widehat {A}]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B\otimes _A\widehat {A}]]></fr:tex>
        (taking into account the fact that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\widehat {A}]]></fr:tex> is faithfully flat over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>).
        We can thus suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>complete</fr:em>.
        Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> be the point over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>.
        By <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.2.2" href="sga1-i.2.2.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="I.2.2" />, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_x]]></fr:tex> is finite over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, and is thus (being flat and radicial over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>) identical to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
        So <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X=Y\coprod  X']]></fr:tex> (disjoint sum).
        But since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is radicial over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X']]></fr:tex> is empty.</fr:li></fr:ol>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
